<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,765,1557]" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,252,765,789]" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Description.</emphasis>
Size: Body length of male 
<quantity box="[534,630,765,789]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="402" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.30 mm</quantity>
, of females 
<quantity box="[754,911,765,789]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3199999999999998" metricValueMax="1.38" metricValueMin="1.26" pageId="5" pageNumber="402" unit="mm" value="1.3199999999999998" valueMax="1.38" valueMin="1.26">1.26–1.38 mm</quantity>
. Maximum body width (= pronotum width) of male 
<quantity box="[470,565,797,821]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="402" unit="mm" value="0.89">0.89 mm</quantity>
, of females 
<quantity box="[686,841,797,821]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.1" metricValueMax="9.399999999999999" metricValueMin="8.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="402" unit="mm" value="0.9099999999999999" valueMax="0.94" valueMin="0.88">0.88–0.94 mm</quantity>
. Eye index (= minimum eye distance: maximum eye width) of male 2.8, of females 2.7–2.9.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,765,1557]" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">
Colour (
<figureCitation box="[232,334,861,885]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[151,190,1506,1525]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[151,1126,219,1440]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. 1–3 – holotype (male), 4–6 – paratype (female). 1, 4 – frontal; 2, 5 – dorsal; 3, 6 – lateral view. In Fig. 6, base of hemielytron not in normal position, covering posterolateral corner of cephalonotum. © NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328261/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Figs. 1–6</figureCitation>
): Dorsum chiefly blackish. Male (
<figureCitation box="[694,793,861,885]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[151,190,1506,1525]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[151,1126,219,1440]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. 1–3 – holotype (male), 4–6 – paratype (female). 1, 4 – frontal; 2, 5 – dorsal; 3, 6 – lateral view. In Fig. 6, base of hemielytron not in normal position, covering posterolateral corner of cephalonotum. © NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328261/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Figs. 1–3</figureCitation>
) cephalonotum with pair of yellow spots near posterolateral margin and with narrow yellow lateral margins; distal margin on hemielytron yellowish, almost transparent. Female (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[747,847,925,949]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="2.[151,190,1506,1525]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-10@2.[151,1126,219,1440]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figs. 1–6. Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. 1–3 – holotype (male), 4–6 – paratype (female). 1, 4 – frontal; 2, 5 – dorsal; 3, 6 – lateral view. In Fig. 6, base of hemielytron not in normal position, covering posterolateral corner of cephalonotum. © NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328261" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328261/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Figs. 4–6</figureCitation>
) cephalonotum, mesoscutellum and hemielytra with several yellow marks of varying shape and extension. Venter of head and thorax mostly yellowish brown, of abdomen dark brown. Legs dark yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,765,1557]" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">
Structural characteristics of brachypterous morph: Head part of cephalonotum with sparse, small punctures, shiny, only at sides weakly tuberculate. Pronotal part of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum tuberculate, each tubercle sloping posteriorly, i.e. posterior slope steeper. Hemielytron with very large, deep punctures; most anterior part with a few small, intermittent tubercles. Mesoscutellum (
<figureCitation box="[399,461,1149,1173]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[151,1126,219,1374]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs.9–16. Structural characters of Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. (9, 11–16) and Mixotrephes hoberlandti Papáček, Štys &amp; Tonner, 1989 (10). 9, 10 – outlines of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum from dorsal view (except M. (P.) pictus sp. nov., all other known Mixotrephes species have the same basic shape of mesoscutellum as M. hoberlandti); 11 – phallosoma; 12 – left paramere; 13 – right paramere; 14 – male abdominal sternum 8; 15 – female subgenital plate; 16 – first right valvula from ventral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm (Figs. 9, 10), B = 0.2 mm (Figs. 14, 15), B = 0.1 mm (Figs. 11–13, 16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) wide with conspicuously convex lateral margins. Rostrum short, almost reaching level of posteroventral corner of prosternal carina; segment 4 ca. 1.5 times as long as segment 3. Forewing without claval and embolar sutures. Hindwings micropterous (examined only in one species). Midventral carinae weakly modified: Prosternal carina with almost rectangular posteroventral corner; mesosternal carina short and acute; metasternal carina with straight ventral outline, posteroventral corner weakly elevated; carinae of abdominal sterna 2–3 pointed, of abdominal sterna 4–6 present as low tubercles, on sternum 6 only in anterior part (in male less distinct than in female).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[113,1089,765,1557]" lastBlockId="7.[113,1089,219,980]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="404" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">
Terminalia of male (
<figureCitation box="[361,492,1405,1429]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[151,1126,219,1374]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs.9–16. Structural characters of Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. (9, 11–16) and Mixotrephes hoberlandti Papáček, Štys &amp; Tonner, 1989 (10). 9, 10 – outlines of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum from dorsal view (except M. (P.) pictus sp. nov., all other known Mixotrephes species have the same basic shape of mesoscutellum as M. hoberlandti); 11 – phallosoma; 12 – left paramere; 13 – right paramere; 14 – male abdominal sternum 8; 15 – female subgenital plate; 16 – first right valvula from ventral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm (Figs. 9, 10), B = 0.2 mm (Figs. 14, 15), B = 0.1 mm (Figs. 11–13, 16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Figs. 11–14</figureCitation>
): Abdominal sternum 8 (
<figureCitation box="[759,836,1405,1429]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[151,1126,219,1374]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs.9–16. Structural characters of Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. (9, 11–16) and Mixotrephes hoberlandti Papáček, Štys &amp; Tonner, 1989 (10). 9, 10 – outlines of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum from dorsal view (except M. (P.) pictus sp. nov., all other known Mixotrephes species have the same basic shape of mesoscutellum as M. hoberlandti); 11 – phallosoma; 12 – left paramere; 13 – right paramere; 14 – male abdominal sternum 8; 15 – female subgenital plate; 16 – first right valvula from ventral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm (Figs. 9, 10), B = 0.2 mm (Figs. 14, 15), B = 0.1 mm (Figs. 11–13, 16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
) slightly asymmetrical, round, longer than wide, processing more caudally on the right side. Pygophore with low, rounded process.Aedeagus simple, phallosoma (
<figureCitation box="[611,684,1469,1493]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[151,1126,219,1374]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs.9–16. Structural characters of Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. (9, 11–16) and Mixotrephes hoberlandti Papáček, Štys &amp; Tonner, 1989 (10). 9, 10 – outlines of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum from dorsal view (except M. (P.) pictus sp. nov., all other known Mixotrephes species have the same basic shape of mesoscutellum as M. hoberlandti); 11 – phallosoma; 12 – left paramere; 13 – right paramere; 14 – male abdominal sternum 8; 15 – female subgenital plate; 16 – first right valvula from ventral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm (Figs. 9, 10), B = 0.2 mm (Figs. 14, 15), B = 0.1 mm (Figs. 11–13, 16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) straight, pin-shaped, slightly flattened, with tapered, bluntly rounded, unmodified apex; somewhat longer than both parameres. Left paramere (
<figureCitation box="[228,306,1533,1557]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[151,1126,219,1374]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs.9–16. Structural characters of Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. (9, 11–16) and Mixotrephes hoberlandti Papáček, Štys &amp; Tonner, 1989 (10). 9, 10 – outlines of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum from dorsal view (except M. (P.) pictus sp. nov., all other known Mixotrephes species have the same basic shape of mesoscutellum as M. hoberlandti); 11 – phallosoma; 12 – left paramere; 13 – right paramere; 14 – male abdominal sternum 8; 15 – female subgenital plate; 16 – first right valvula from ventral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm (Figs. 9, 10), B = 0.2 mm (Figs. 14, 15), B = 0.1 mm (Figs. 11–13, 16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="402">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
) slightly longer that right one; basally robust with wide, round posterior lamella, distally hook-shaped with very conspicuous dense and long setae. Right paramere (
<figureCitation box="[121,199,251,276]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[151,1126,219,1374]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs.9–16. Structural characters of Mixotrephes (Pictotrephes) pictus sp. nov. (9, 11–16) and Mixotrephes hoberlandti Papáček, Štys &amp; Tonner, 1989 (10). 9, 10 – outlines of cephalonotum and mesoscutellum from dorsal view (except M. (P.) pictus sp. nov., all other known Mixotrephes species have the same basic shape of mesoscutellum as M. hoberlandti); 11 – phallosoma; 12 – left paramere; 13 – right paramere; 14 – male abdominal sternum 8; 15 – female subgenital plate; 16 – first right valvula from ventral view. Scale bars: A = 1.0 mm (Figs. 9, 10), B = 0.2 mm (Figs. 14, 15), B = 0.1 mm (Figs. 11–13, 16)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="404">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) nearly upright, apically antero-posteriorly flattened, spoon shaped; only with few minute setae on posterior surface.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5328267" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5328267" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5328267/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="403" startId="6.[151,191,1402,1421]" targetBox="[151,1126,219,1359]" targetPageId="6">
